It's an understatement to say 2021 was hard. Honestly, it absolutely wrecked me, and then came back for seconds. This year I lost a member of my section in band to brain cancer at the tail end of my senior year. Because of me being section leader and having a ton of grieving kids I had to stay strong. I had to be supportive and a beacon of hope even if it ment not expressing my weakness or even grief. Between this, having to perform on the marimba at his funeral, and immediately having to do an interview with the damn newspaper about him the LITERAL NEXT DAY after he passed, I don't think I really got the chance to fully grieve. It has caused me to deal with the worst on and off again depression of my entire life, wrecked my graduation, my summer, and shook my faith to It's core and I'm still not 100% sure what I believe anymore. And honestly I hate talking about how it has affected me because I feel as though it makes me selfish because I can't imagine what his family is going through. Everytime I feel as though I am doing better I crash and burn almost immediately because I'll be reminded of him. There was so much this kid never experienced. Past the age of 14 he never got to live a normal life again. Towards the last year of his life he lost all feeling in his right side and was unable to get his license, which was deeply upsetting to him as he wanted to drive so badly. He never really got to experience the beauty of a true relationship, have kids, vote, or really grow up at all. It's not fair. But cancer doesn't care about what's fair. And neither does fate/God whatever you believe in. But something that has brought me peace is to know that he is no longer suffering and I hope by knowing that, that each day will get a little easier. I guess the whole point of this little rant is to just let anyone out there know that someone understands what you're going through. And they're willing to talk to you and help you through it and also help themselves get through their situation. You are never alone.
